43. In Old Attio Comedy the number of actors was limited to three¹ These three formed a tronpe, while the chorus, which might be regarded as a fourth actor, was an indepen- dent body. Of course, mute characters were also freely employed. When the chorus disappeared, the number of actore was probably increased. Certainly on the Roman stage the number was usually more than three, for of the extant comedies, in only two, the Cistellaria and Stichus of Plautus, would three actors suffice.
